# 1 Cloud computing benefits 

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010190121.png)

Cloud computing is an on-demand delivery of IT resources over the internet, usually with pay-as-you-go pricing.
Instead of buying, owning, and maintaining physical data centers and servers, you can access technology services, such as computing power, storage, and databases, on an as-needed bases from a cloud provider such as Amazon Web Services (AWS)



As you begin to learn about cloud computing, consider why a company might choose a particular cloud computing approach to address their business needs. This section of the course explores six benefits of cloud computing. As you learn about each benefit, think about how you might have experienced the benefit at work or during other computing activities

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010190124.png)

Six key benefits of cloud computing are:
• Pay as you go: You pay for computing resources that you consume instead of investing heavily in data centers and servers before you know how you will use them.
• Benefit from massive economies of scale: Customers pay lower prices as AWS achieves higher economies of scale due to the aggregated use of the large number of AWS customers.
• Stop guessing capacity: With cloud computing, you no longer have to guess your infrastructure capacity needs. You can access as much or as little capacity as you need, and scale up and down as required with only a few minutes notice.
• Increase speed and agility: IT resources are only a click away, which means that you reduce the time to make those resources available to your developers from weeks to minutes, which leads to increased agility for your organization.
• Realize cost savings: With cloud computing, you can focus on your customers by offering improved products and services instead of maintaining physical data centers.
• Go global in minutes: You can deploy your application in multiple Regions around the world with a few clicks. This means that you can provide lower latency and a better experience for your customers at a minimal cost

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010190130.png)

AWS offers a broad set of cloud-based products and services, including compute, storage, databases, analytics, networking, mobile, developer tools, management tools, Internet of Things (IoT), security, and enterprise applications. These services help organizations move faster, lower IT costs, and scale. AWS is trusted by large enterprises and start-ups to power a wide variety of workloads including web and mobile applications, game development, data processing and warehousing, storage, archives, and many others.
Reference For more information, see “AWS Cloud Products” (https://aws.amazon.com/products/).


# 2 AWS Global infrastructure 

Infrastructure, like data centers and networking connectivity, exists as the foundation of every cloud application. In AWS, this physical infrastructure makes up the AWS Global Infrastructure, which includes Regions, Availability Zones, and Edge Locations.

## 2.1 Region

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010190142.png)

AWS Regions are physical geographic locations around the world where AWS hosts data centers. A Region consists of three or more Availability Zones in the geographical area. Regions are named after the location where they reside.
For example, in the United States, we have a Region in Northern Virginia called the Northern Virginia Region and a Region in Oregon called the Oregon Region.
At AWS, we currently have Regions in North America, South America, Europe, China, Asia Pacific, South Africa, and the Middle East, and we are continuously expanding to meet the needs of our customers.
When you use AWS, you choose the location for your resources by selecting a Region.
For the most updated information on region locations and availability zones, visit https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/global-infrastructure/regions_az/

AWS Regions are physical geographic locations around the world where AWS hosts data centers. A Region consists of three or more Availability Zones in the geographical area. Regions are named after the location where they reside.
For example, in the United States, we have a Region in Northern Virginia called the Northern Virginia Region and a Region in Oregon called the Oregon Region.
At AWS, we currently have Regions in North America, South America, Europe, China, Asia Pacific, South Africa, and the Middle East, and we are continuously expanding to meet the needs of our customers.
When you use AWS, you choose the location for your resources by selecting a Region.
For the most updated information on region locations and availability zones, visit https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/global-infrastructure/regions_az


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010192658.png)

When determining the right Region for your services, data, and applications, consider these four business factors:
Latency: When possible, select a Region that is close to your customers so you can deliver content to them quickly. For example, if your customers are in Japan, you might select the Asia Pacific (Tokyo) Region for your applications.
Pricing: Costs vary by Region. For example, if you run an application in the United States and Brazil, Brazil’s tax structure might result in your company paying 50% more to run the same workload out of the São Paulo Region compared to the Oregon Region.
Service availability: Some AWS services are available in only a select number of Regions. You should always check the service availability before selecting a Region.
Data compliance: Depending on your company and location, you might need to run your data out of specific locations. For example, if your company requires all of its data to reside within the boundaries of the UK, you would choose the London Region. Not all companies have location-specific data regulations or compliance requirements.


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010190156.png)


An Availability Zone (AZ) consists of one or more data centers with redundant power, networking, and connectivity. AZs give customers the ability to operate highly available, fault-tolerant, and scalable applications and databases.
Even though AZs are close enough to have low latency (latency is the time between when content is requested and received), they are not built directly next to one another

# 4 Edge locations 


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010190220.png)


Edge locations are global locations where content is cached. For example, if your media content is in London and you want to share video files with your customers in Tokyo, you could have the videos cached in an edge location closest to Tokyo. This would enable your customers to access the cached videos more quickly than accessing them from London.
Currently, we have over 218 edge locations globally.

# 5 AWS Service management 

After you deploy your solution in the AWS Cloud, you manage it logically through the AWS application programming interface (API). You can make API calls to create, delete, and change any AWS service or product. The three main ways to make API calls are to use the AWS Management Console, AWS Command Line Interface (AWS CLI), and AWS software development kits (AWS SDKs).

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010192912.png)


The AWS Management Console is a web-based interface for accessing and managing AWS services. You can access recently used services and search for other services by name, keyword, or acronym. The console is also available as a mobile application.
You can also use the AWS Command Line Interface (AWS CLI). AWS CLI helps you control multiple AWS services directly from the command line in one tool. AWS CLI is available for users on Windows, macOS, and Linux. By using AWS CLI, you can automate the actions that your services and applications perform through scripts.
Another option for accessing and managing AWS services are the software development kits (SDKs). AWS SDKs help you use AWS services through an API designed for your programming language or platform. Our SDKs can help you use AWS services with your existing applications or help you create new applications that will run on AWS.
To help you get started with using SDKs, we provide documentation and sample code for each supported programming language. Supported programming languages include C++, Go, Java, JavaScript, Python, Node.js, .NET, and more.


# 6 Security and the aws shared responsibility model 

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193001.png)


When customers use AWS, they do not have to manage every single aspect of their hosting solution. Instead, they can rely on AWS to manage portions of their workload, like running the day-to-day data center operations. With that in mind, who do you think is responsible for security? Is it AWS? Is it the customer? Or is it the customer and AWS?

The answer is C. Both. Both the customer and AWS are responsible for securing AWS solutions.
When you use the AWS Cloud, managing security and compliance is a shared responsibility between you and AWS. To depict this shared responsibility, we created the shared responsibility model.


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193025.png)


The shared responsibility model shows the division of customer responsibilities (commonly
referred to as “security in the cloud”) and AWS responsibilities (commonly referred to as “security of the cloud”).
Think about how a construction company builds a building and makes sure that the building is stable and secure. Once the building is ready, you can rent an apartment located on one of its floors. Once rented, you must lock your apartment door to protect your belongings. In this scenario, AWS is the construction company, and you are the tenant.



![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193055.png)


As shown in the model, customers are responsible for security in the cloud. This means that when you use any AWS service, you are responsible for properly configuring the service and your applications, in addition to ensuring that your data is secure.
The level of responsibility you have depends on the service. Some services require you to perform all the necessary security configuration and management tasks, while other more abstracted services require you to only manage the data and control access to your resources. For example, for compute services such as Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2), you control the operating system and application platform, in addition to encrypting, protecting, and managing customer data. For services like Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), you are responsible for managing customer data and protecting it through client-side encryption.


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193105.png)




AWS is responsible for security of the cloud. This means that we protect and secure the infrastructure that runs all the services offered in the AWS Cloud.
We protect and secure AWS Regions, Availability Zones, and data centers, down to the physical security of the buildings.
AWS manages the hardware, software, and networking components that run AWS services, such as the physical servers, host operating systems, virtualization layers, and AWS networking components.
The level of responsibility AWS has depends on the service. For example, for compute services such as Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2), AWS manages the underlying infrastructure and foundation services. For services that require little management from customers, such as Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), AWS operates the infrastructure layer, operating system, and platforms, in addition to server-side encryption and data protection.




# 7 Aws identity and acces management IAM

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193152.png)
AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) is a web service that helps you manage secure access to your AWS accounts and resources.
With IAM, you can create and manage AWS users, applications, and connected services. By using permissions, you can control how users, applications, and services access your AWS resources.


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193209.png)


To help control access and manage identities in your AWS account, IAM offers the following features:
• IAM is global. It is not specific to any one Region. • By default, IAM is integrated with many AWS services. • You can grant other people permission to administer and use resources in your AWS account without having to share your password and key.
• IAM supports multi-factor authentication (MFA). You can add MFA to your account and to individual users for extra security.
• IAM supports identity federation. You can allow users who already have passwords elsewhere – for example, in your corporate network or with an internet identity provider – to get temporary access to your AWS account.
• IAM is a feature of your AWS account offered at no additional charge. You are only charged when you access other AWS services using your IAM users.



![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193218.png)


When you first create an AWS account, you begin with a single sign-in identity that has complete access to all AWS services and resources in the account. This identity is called the AWS root user. The root user is accessed by signing in with the email address and password that you used to create the account.
The following credentials are associated with the AWS root user: • User name and password used to create the AWS account: Permits you to access the AWS Management Console.
• Access keys (composed of access key ID and secret access key): Permits you to make programmatic requests from the AWS CLI or AWS API. Similar to a user name and password combination, you need both the access key ID and secret access key to authenticate your requests in AWS CLI or AWS API. Access keys should be managed with the same security as an email address and password.
To ensure the safety of the root user, follow these best practices: • Choose a strong password. • Enable multi-factor authentication for the root user. • Never share your root user password or access keys with anyone. • Disable or delete the access keys associated with the root user. • Create an IAM user for administrative tasks or everyday tasks.

Using a user name and password to log in to an AWS account is considered to be a single-factor authentication. Single-factor authentication is the simplest and most common form of authentication. Even if you choose a strong password for your root account, your account is still considered at risk.
For example, if a bad actor figures out your password through social engineering, bots, or scripts, then they can access your account and delete valuable data. They could also spin up an expensive cryptocurrency mining operation, leaving you with the bill. To help protect your account from malicious acts, you can use multi-factor authentication (MFA).
With MFA, even if someone guesses or figures out your user name and password, they cannot gain access to your account without the numbers generated by the virtual MFA device.
We recommended that you enable MFA immediately after you create your AWS account.
Reference For more information, visit the AWS MFA website: https://aws.amazon.com/iam/features/mfa



## 7.1 IAM user 

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193452.png)




An IAM user is an identity that you create in AWS. It represents a person or application that interacts with AWS services and resources. It consists of a name and credentials. You are responsible for any cost incurred by the IAM users that you create.
As a best practice, when creating IAM roles for users, require MFA for additional security. With MFA, users have a device that generates a response to an authentication challenge.
By default, when you create a new IAM user in AWS, it has no permissions associated with it. To allow an IAM user to perform specific actions in AWS, such as implement resources, you must grant the IAM user the necessary permissions


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193501.png)

An IAM policy is a JSON document that allows or denies permissions to AWS services and resources. IAM policies permit you to customize users’ levels of access to resources. As a best practice, follow the security principle of least privilege.
Here is a JSON document example of an IAM policy that permits a user to start and stop EC2 instances inside an AWS account: 
{
"Version": "2012-10-17", "Statement": [ 
        {
        "Effect": "Allow", "Action": [
        “ec2:StartInstances", “ec2:StopInstances” ],
        "Resource": “arn:aws:ec2:*:*:instance/*“
        } 
    ] 
}

The four major JSON elements in the example are as follows: 
• Version: Defines the version of the policy language 
• Effect: Specifies whether the statement will allow or deny access 
• Action: Describes the type of action that should be allowed or denied 
• Resource: Specifies the object that the policy statement covers

------

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193456.png)

Granting permission by assigning policies at the user level is a good idea, but what if you have 3,000 users in your AWS account? Administrating access can become a challenge. To ease this challenge, AWS created IAM groups.

An IAM group is a collection of IAM users. When you assign an IAM policy to a group, all users in the group are granted permissions specified by the policy.
To manage groups, you might want to organize IAM groups by job functions. For example, if your company is building a software application and you want to control the process, you could organize your developers into an IAM developer group, your testers into an IAM QA group, and your administrators into an IAM admin group. Then, you could create and assign unique IAM policies to the groups, instead of individual users.
IAM groups can have many users, and users can belong to many groups. IAM groups cannot belong to other groups.
Now, consider an application developer that hasn’t switched jobs permanently, but instead, rotates to different roles throughout the day. In this case, the employee can get the access they need through IAM roles.



--------



![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193536.png)



![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010193539.png)



An IAM role is an identity that can be assumed by a person or a service to gain temporary access to other AWS resources or services. When you assume an IAM role, you get temporary security credentials for your session.
IAM roles can be used by the following entities: • IAM user in the same or different AWS account as the role • AWS service • External user authenticated by an external identity provider (IdP) service that is compatible with SAML 2.0 or OpenID Connect, or a custom-built identity broker
For example, imagine that you have a business with 5,000 employees that must access an AWS account. You already have an identity provider in place that allows your employees to log in to their work laptops. Instead of creating 5,000 IAM accounts, you can use IAM roles to grant access to existing identities from your enterprise user directory, known as federated users.
AWS services can also assume an IAM role to perform actions in your AWS account on your behalf. When you set up an AWS service, you must define a role, which includes all the permissions required, for the service to assume by following the documented requirements for that service.
Keep in mind that roles assigned to an AWS service are account specific.
As a best practice, IAM roles are ideal for situations in which access to services or resources must be granted temporarily.

Which of the following accurately describes the relationship between Regions, Availability Zones, and data centers?
A. Availability Zones are clusters of Regions. Regions are clusters of data centers. 
B. Data centers are clusters of Availability Zones. Regions are clusters of Availability Zones. 
C. Regions are clusters of Availability Zones. Availability Zones consist of one or more data centers.
D. Data centers are clusters of Regions. Regions are clusters of Availability Zones.


The correct response option is C. Regions are clusters of Availability Zones. Availability Zones consist of one or more data centers.
Explanation: The AWS Global Infrastructure is nested for high availability and redundancy. AWS Regions are clusters of Availability Zones that are connected by highly available and redundant high-speed links, and Availability Zones consist of one or more data centers that are also connected by highly available and redundant high-speed links.
